article.headline: Sun Devils solidify NCAA Tournament hopes
article.linkText: Arizona State feels like dancing after beating Ducks
article.story: TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- The personal achievements meant little to Curtis Millage and Tommy Smith. Arizona State winning meant a probable extension of their season. Millage tied his season high with 27 points and Smith tied his career high with 24 as the Sun Devils made up a four-point halftime deficit to beat Oregon 91-77 Thursday night. "We weren't doing what we were supposed to,'' said Smith, who also had 11 rebounds and five assists. "We were outrebounded, and just the little stuff that goes to toughness. We just fought back.'' Ike Diogu had 17 points and 14 rebounds, helping the Sun Devils (18-10, 10-7) snap a season-worst three-game losing streak. Luke Ridnour had 26 points, seven rebounds and six assists for the Ducks (20-8, 10-7), and Luke Jackson scored 20 points. The Ducks and Sun Devils will meet in the first round of the conference tournament next week, but both hoped to solidify their NCAA Tournament chances with a late regular-season victory. Oregon plays No. 1 Arizona on Saturday, and the Sun Devils finish up with Oregon State. "We feel like we need another one somewhere, so this was a tough game to lose,'' Ridnour said. "It hurts, because we felt we had control of it.'' Oregon played confidently in building a 45-41 halftime lead. But the Ducks had three turnovers in the first 3:30 of the second half, and Arizona State went on a 14-2 run, opening a 55-47 lead when Diogu tipped in his own missed shot with 16:10 to go. Shawn Redhage, who had 12 points in just his third start of the season, forced another turnover with his defense on Ridnour, who threw the ball into the backcourt. Smith grabbed it and dunked, sending the Sun Devils to a 58-48 lead with 15:06 remaining. Oregon got within 58-56 after three-point plays by Andre Joseph and James Davis, and, after the Sun Devils responded, Ridnour cut the deficit to 69-66 with a 3-pointer with 7:16 to go. But Joseph blew two layups and Ridnour picked up two offensive fouls down the stretch. Smith drove the baseline for a dunk, got an offensive rebound and made a putback during a 13-4 spurt that opened an 80-67 lead with 2:00 left. "It was just a hard-fought ballgame,'' Arizona State coach Rob Evans said. "We got behind and came back. We made a run and they made a run on us, and we just kept battling.'' No more than four points separated the teams in the first half, and there were 12 lead changes -- the last when Joseph made a layup with 1:18 to play. Ridnour, who had 20 points at halftime, made his fourth 3-pointer of the half 28 seconds later and followed two free throw by Millage with two of his own with 6.7 seconds to go for a 45-41 halftime lead. "In the second half, ASU became the aggressor,'' Oregon coach Ernie Kent said. "Defensively, they got up on us, and we were forcing shots that didn't go.''
